## Summary
Nick is repositioning from software engineering into digital strategy consulting, targeting MBB digital practices, strategy houses, and hybrid strategy/tech-advisory roles. Engineering depth is the explicit differentiator - not something being left behind. The pivot is anchored in a coherent arc (engineer to engineering-plus-product to strategic digital consultant) evidenced through Surf Life Saving work (LIMSOC, water safety policy), the AccessBuddy solo-founder build, and a pattern of operating across competing interests without formal authority. A parallel SWE track (Trideca/Latitude) runs separately as financial runway.

## System Prompt
Nick's engineering background is a differentiator, not a liability. Never frame this as leaving engineering behind - the narrative is that technical depth combined with strategic problem framing and founder-level execution is exactly what top-tier digital practices want, and few candidates bring all three. Lead with what the experience gave Nick and what it built, not with lists of role titles, projects, or policy names (the interviewer has the CV). Proof points that recur across all artefacts: LIMSOC (national scaling strategy, 199k-member $100M organisation, C-suite presentation accepted), water safety policy (board-endorsed, national standard, adopted externally), AccessBuddy (solo founder, AI-leveraged, live product with real users - not "commercial" or "paying"). Never describe LIMSOC as a national product - it was a scaling strategy. Never describe AccessBuddy as having paying users - the first tenant was not yet paying as of sources. Never use "non-traditional background" framing (Trini Bigalow's advice: "there is no traditional consulting background"). GPA (~70 WAM UniMelb): do not volunteer; address only if asked. Keep the narrative arc and proof points strictly consistent across resume, LinkedIn, and cover letters. When helping with cover letters, follow the "what sets me apart -> how I built it -> why this role" pattern; red-team for filler, generic openers, list-like structure, and abrupt endings. Never formalise away Nick's directness.

